just went out on Friday. So if anybody is interested or thinking about giving a talk,

00:03:59.839 --> 00:04:05.199
go check that out. Would love to hear from you all. But also, I love getting to use the Hangout

00:04:05.199 --> 00:04:11.119
as a way to meet people who are going to be at conference too. So as you get your tickets and

00:04:11.119 --> 00:04:14.960
let people know here in the chat, it would be great to be able to connect with each other

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:21.359
to get to meet in person too. But with all that, thank you all so much for being here and joining

00:04:21.359 --> 00:04:27.200
us today. We're so excited to be joined by our other co-host for the day, Noah Branham,

00:04:27.279 --> 00:04:34.399
Senior Manager of Analytics at DraftKings. And Noah, I'd love to have you introduce yourself a

00:04:34.399 --> 00:04:39.040
bit here and share a little bit about your role today, but also something you like to do outside

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:45.440
of work too. Yeah, totally. Thank you guys so much for having me. I'm a big RStudio fan,

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:51.519
I should mention that. Yeah, so as Rachel said, I'm a Senior Manager at DraftKings. I've been

00:04:51.519 --> 00:04:57.600
there for about two and a half years. I oversee measurements of a number of different initiatives,

00:04:57.600 --> 00:05:06.079
but mostly our reach marketing initiatives. So TV, audio, and influencer, and then our monetization

00:05:06.079 --> 00:05:12.720
measurement efforts. So basically measuring how our external marketing affects our existing

00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:18.399
customer base and their types of play. So it's a lot of fun. We have a great time, definitely a

00:05:18.399 --> 00:05:24.480
very sports-focused culture. And previously I was in the insurance industry for a little over

00:05:24.480 --> 00:05:31.279
six years. I did some work on staffing optimization, which was a lot of fun. As insurance companies,

00:05:31.279 --> 00:05:37.519
staffing is like a major expense for them. And then for a period of time, I worked in pricing

00:05:37.519 --> 00:05:42.399
predictive modeling. So yeah, it's been, I've had a lot of fun, a lot of really interesting roles

00:05:42.399 --> 00:05:47.679
that's given me some pretty interesting experience. And then in terms of things I do for fun,

00:05:48.559 --> 00:05:54.559
lately, I would say I've been really into running. I ran my first half marathon this last year,

00:05:54.559 --> 00:06:00.480
and then I really like to barbecue, actually. I just got a smoker in the last three years. So

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:04.480
that's kind of a fun weekend activity for, it pairs well with football.

00:06:06.079 --> 00:06:11.040
I love that. I just made the decision recently to run the Boston Marathon

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:15.679
this year. So that's awesome. Connect over some running tips.

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:22.000
Noah, I think maybe for the audience here, it might be helpful to give a little more background

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:28.559
on what DraftKings is as well to help us with some of the questions we're asking.

00:06:29.119 --> 00:06:34.799
Yeah, totally. I'll give a brief history on the industry. So sports betting really didn't become

00:06:34.799 --> 00:06:41.200
legal, I think, until 2018. So before that, FanDuel and DraftKings were the major players

00:06:41.200 --> 00:06:45.679
in the industry, but they had focused on a different type of game called daily fantasy

00:06:45.679 --> 00:06:52.559
sports. And so that was legal since, I think, 2012, where essentially you could set a lineup

00:06:52.559 --> 00:06:57.839
of players, and you enter a contest, and whoever's lineup has the highest points,

00:06:57.839 --> 00:07:03.519
but then you win that contest. And so that was deemed legal. But then in 2018,

00:07:03.519 --> 00:07:07.920
actual sports betting became legal, where you can bet on individual game outcomes and

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:12.880
what we call player props, which are player-specific bets within a game.

00:07:13.679 --> 00:07:18.640
And I believe New Jersey was the first state, and a number of states, I think it's 26 total now,

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:22.799
have been rolled out over the last now seven years.

00:07:25.119 --> 00:07:32.399
Nice. Thank you. Yeah, we know DraftKings pretty well in our household here with our friend group,

00:07:32.399 --> 00:07:39.359
but I think it's helpful to just share with everybody too. Could you maybe share a little

00:07:39.359 --> 00:07:44.959
bit with us first about also how you got into data? And if you weren't working in data,

00:07:44.959 --> 00:07:51.760
what other career path would you have explored? That's a great question. So in college,

00:07:53.200 --> 00:08:00.320
my kind of like focus had really been to try to go into politics. And so I had actually worked for a

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:05.519
U.S. representative going into my senior year of college, and then worked for her briefly

00:08:06.559 --> 00:08:13.440
for a short period of time right after college. And it was a really good experience, but I realized

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:20.720
pretty quickly for me that it wasn't for me. The ironic thing was during that time, I was in charge

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:24.000
of dealing with a lot of different data and organizing data. And that's when I really

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:29.359
started to get into learning Visual Basic for applications. And I was like, okay, I like this

00:08:29.359 --> 00:08:34.080
aspect of the job. I just didn't like the other components of the job. And that's what led me down

00:08:34.080 --> 00:08:41.440
to data analytics. And this was in 2009 and 2010. So analytics and data science weren't

00:08:41.440 --> 00:08:48.000
as prevalent as they were now. But coming out of the Great Recession, companies were just trying

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.080
to be more data-driven and more efficient going forward. And I think that really helped spur on

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:58.880
the data science movement. Obviously, a lot of data was being created just because of technology

00:08:58.880 --> 00:09:02.559
as well. But that opened up a lot of opportunities.

00:09:05.039 --> 00:09:10.400
Thank you. I was also kind of wondering, you said that you measure the performance of marketing

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:17.760
campaigns just like as an overall what your team does. Could you share maybe an example of a problem

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:22.159
that your team is tackling now or that they've tackled in the past to help us kind of understand

00:09:22.159 --> 00:09:27.599
the day-to-day challenges that you see? Yeah. So I can give an example. I will say

00:09:28.239 --> 00:09:34.239
I was told I can't go into too many specifics just for competitive reasons. But I will say

00:09:34.799 --> 00:09:41.919
essentially, companies like DraftKings or my previous employer, Liberty Mutual Insurance,

00:09:41.919 --> 00:09:48.559
spend a lot of money on marketing. And so not only is it a lot of money, but it's across different

00:09:48.559 --> 00:09:54.479
channels. And so a problem that a lot of firms, regardless of industry, are trying to figure out

00:09:54.479 --> 00:10:01.359
is what is the right amount of spend that they should be spending by channel? And so you can

00:10:01.359 --> 00:10:07.359
measure that through what's called multi-touch attribution, which is measuring direct effects

00:10:07.359 --> 00:10:13.520
of each individual marketing channel. So let's say you have an influencer on Twitter that is

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:20.719
posting about your company. The attribution could be directly measuring the people clicking on the

00:10:20.719 --> 00:10:27.119
link and then coming to your site. Or it could be something like estimating the overall impact

00:10:27.119 --> 00:10:31.119
by understanding the synergies between the different marketing channels. And that is

00:10:31.119 --> 00:10:37.440
often done using regression and what's called a media mix model. And so that's much more high

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:42.799
level. And so typically, firms will institute both types of methodologies to get a better

00:10:42.799 --> 00:10:50.080
understanding of how well their overall marketing is performing. Thank you. I think that that helps

00:10:50.080 --> 00:10:56.159
a lot without going into nitty gritty details. There's also a sort of cheeky question on the

00:10:56.159 --> 00:11:01.119
Slido that I really liked, which is, are you allowed to bet on sports given your potential

00:11:01.119 --> 00:11:06.000
sort of insider info based on the research that you do? Or do you get to bet? That's a great

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:11.919
question. Yeah. So we're not allowed to bet on draftkings. So I can bet on a competitor app

00:11:12.799 --> 00:11:18.159
just because we don't set their lines. But we are not allowed to bet internally, no.

00:11:20.799 --> 00:11:27.359
Thanks. Travis, I see you just put a question into the chat. Do you want to jump in here first?

00:11:28.159 --> 00:11:34.799
Sure. Thanks. So my question is about APIs. And draftkings API is not open or

00:11:35.359 --> 00:11:39.840
particularly transparently documented, which is OK. I'm sure that's some kind of business

00:11:39.840 --> 00:11:44.159
decision that's made. I'm curious about what goes behind if that's anywhere near your domain,

00:11:44.559 --> 00:11:50.640
what decides whether or not to open such things up. So myself, I geek out on PlayerProp.

00:11:51.599 --> 00:11:54.960
That's fairly often. I've met some other people in this Hangout that do the same.

00:11:54.960 --> 00:12:00.559
And we all have this patchwork put together of finding out what's behind the draftkings website

00:12:00.559 --> 00:12:05.679
and crafting our own APIs and things like that. But a paid version of an API would be amazing,

00:12:05.679 --> 00:12:09.840
even if people would pay for it. But why doesn't draftkings, for example, pursue that, if you know?

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:16.159
That's a great question. I don't know. But I can definitely ask. I can definitely ask.

00:12:16.799 --> 00:12:21.520
Fun. Yeah. I mentioned in my question, you could get some influences, you know, like

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:26.719
we have our Python influencers who are here who would love to be that person for you.

00:12:26.719 --> 00:12:27.760
OK, sounds good.

00:12:29.599 --> 00:12:32.880
I love it, Travis. Pitching the data influencers. Way to go.

00:12:34.479 --> 00:12:37.599
I see another Slido question that just came in. And it was,

00:12:38.239 --> 00:12:42.159
I'm interested in the mix of Python and R at draftkings.

00:12:42.159 --> 00:12:45.200
What would you use R for? And what would you use Python for?

00:12:46.080 --> 00:12:52.719
Yeah, it's a great question. I would say in general, a lot of the teams use Python.

00:12:52.719 --> 00:12:58.400
My team specifically definitely has a good mix. I would say right now I have an analyst

00:12:58.400 --> 00:13:03.280
working on Bayesian models. And so we leverage PYMC for that. But a lot of our

00:13:04.159 --> 00:13:06.799
mixed effects models will use R for.

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:14.880
Awesome. It looks like Abigail was just mentioning PYMC in the chat.

00:13:18.239 --> 00:13:23.440
I had a question. I know that you, just from previous conversations,

00:13:23.440 --> 00:13:28.479
you've worked at bigger and smaller companies. And I have, too. Very small to very, very large.

00:13:28.559 --> 00:13:32.239
And I'm kind of wondering what the difference that you've seen

00:13:32.239 --> 00:13:34.960
is in working in data in small and large companies.

00:13:35.679 --> 00:13:42.400
Yeah, that's a great question. I think that was actually a very big career decision for myself.

00:13:42.400 --> 00:13:48.080
I think when I started out, I really wanted to work at a smaller company and get a lot of

00:13:48.080 --> 00:13:53.440
experience in a lot of different areas. But I found out that I was, being a jack of all trades

00:13:53.840 --> 00:14:01.679
is being a master of none. And I think for me, that was good for a short period of time.

00:14:01.679 --> 00:14:06.640
But I ultimately started to get asked these very difficult questions by board members

00:14:06.640 --> 00:14:11.840
of these different startups. And I couldn't answer them because I just didn't have the skills at the

00:14:11.840 --> 00:14:17.039
time. And that's what really actually pushed me to go from a more traditional analytics role to

00:14:17.039 --> 00:14:21.520
go into data science at a larger company. Because not only were there resources,

00:14:21.520 --> 00:14:25.280
and by resources, I mean other really, really smart people who can help me out,

00:14:25.280 --> 00:14:30.799
who had PhDs and help train me, but resources in terms of being able to fund going to grad

00:14:30.799 --> 00:14:35.599
school and pay for courses and whatnot. And that really helped elevate my career. On paper,

00:14:35.599 --> 00:14:40.320
it might have looked like a slight step back, but it was really just a way of investing in myself.

00:14:41.599 --> 00:14:46.960
That was my next question. What approaches did you take over the years when you decided,

00:14:46.960 --> 00:14:52.479
hey, it's time for me to level up? Was it just grad school? Was there other stuff in there?

00:14:53.119 --> 00:14:59.440
Yeah. I think at first, I really tried to learn as much as I could on my own. I leveraged

00:15:00.239 --> 00:15:05.200
data camp a lot. I talked to my friends who were a lot more technical than myself.

00:15:06.080 --> 00:15:14.080
But I realized you can only go so far doing those things on your own. And so that was one of the

00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:18.000
benefits of going to a place like Liberty Mutual, where there was a lot of really smart people. We

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:23.760
had a data science community, even within Liberty Mutual, that we had resources that we could talk

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:30.239
through. And then one thing that I did that I actually really tried to focus on was I looked

00:15:30.239 --> 00:15:37.440
at a graduate school program's entire agenda, and I tried to learn as much as I could. So then when

00:15:37.440 --> 00:15:43.919
I went to graduate school, it wasn't as much of a chore. And some people in the graduate program

00:15:44.320 --> 00:15:49.119
struggled. But for me, it was more just filling in a lot of those gaps.

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:57.200
Thank you. Well, while we're starting to talk about your journey, I remember when we first met

00:15:57.200 --> 00:16:02.960
on our call, we were chatting a little bit about thinking of your career as trimesters. And I

00:16:02.960 --> 00:16:06.880
thought that might be a helpful conversation for the group here. Would you be able to share a little

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:12.960
bit about what you mean by that? Yeah, totally. So I would say the first trimester was really just

00:16:13.760 --> 00:16:18.640
getting familiar with working in the corporate world. And so for me, a lot of that was how to

00:16:18.640 --> 00:16:24.479
conduct and lead meetings, how to get your basic data analytics skills in order. So understanding,

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:30.320
at the time, the tool of choice was really more Excel for me, just based on where I worked.

00:16:30.320 --> 00:16:35.679
And then getting into SQL, learning how to create presentations, and actually share those

00:16:35.679 --> 00:16:40.719
presentations out and create clean decks. That was really the first trimester for me. And then

00:16:40.719 --> 00:16:44.080
that's where, like I mentioned before, I was starting to run into those struggles with

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:48.239
how to answer really difficult business questions. So the second trimester was really

00:16:49.919 --> 00:16:54.000
getting into the data science world, understanding predictive modeling and optimization problems,

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:59.200
and how to solve them. And I think a big thing is understanding the business problem,

00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:04.560
and then knowing what type of technique you need to do to then tackle that problem. I think a lot

00:17:04.560 --> 00:17:09.520
of people really struggle with that. And I think that's a really powerful thing to be able to

00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:16.000
understand. So I spent a lot of time doing that. And I was almost pushed into management roles

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:22.479
eventually. And so that's really my third trimester, which is the manager trimester,

00:17:22.479 --> 00:17:27.920
which I think was the biggest adjustment. I think what gets you success as an analyst doesn't

00:17:27.920 --> 00:17:36.400
necessarily get you success as a manager. So you have to reframe your goals and time management,

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:39.199
and how you spend your hours during the day.

00:17:41.520 --> 00:17:46.800
I think that whole conversation on, or we could have a whole conversation on becoming a manager.

00:17:47.920 --> 00:17:53.520
But Rob, I see you asked a question in the chat just a few seconds ago. Do you want to jump in

00:17:53.520 --> 00:18:05.760
here next? That's Rob. Can you hear me? Yep, we can. Great. Yes, thank you. I was just curious

00:18:05.760 --> 00:18:13.280
if you had any recommendations on soft skills, the main soft skills you use, and any resources

00:18:13.280 --> 00:18:19.920
for those of us that are maybe more technical of reaching those who are on the less technical side.

00:18:19.920 --> 00:18:26.400
Because a lot of times I'll have what I think is an amazing presentation or an amazing outcome,

00:18:26.400 --> 00:18:30.880
but then trying to frame that for maybe somebody who isn't as far into the details.

00:18:31.839 --> 00:18:37.680
Yeah, that's an excellent question. I think your problem is actually a very common problem that

00:18:38.479 --> 00:18:44.880
I call it when the rubber meets the road in data science. I've seen really excellent data scientists

00:18:44.880 --> 00:18:50.239
build fantastic models, but they haven't really been able to have the impact that they need to

00:18:50.239 --> 00:18:54.560
be successful in the role because they can't communicate their work. Somebody I think recently

00:18:54.560 --> 00:19:00.400
said to me, your analysis is 50% of it, but communicating your analysis is the other 50%

00:19:00.560 --> 00:19:06.239
as well. So that's an excellent question. I think there isn't an exact resource that I have for you,

00:19:06.239 --> 00:19:12.800
but I can tell you what I do, which is I try to find someone on our team who is not familiar

00:19:12.800 --> 00:19:18.239
with our work, and I ask to spend like 30 minutes with them to just share our presentation with them

00:19:18.239 --> 00:19:23.520
just to get their feedback because it will all be new to them as it would be to an executive

00:19:23.520 --> 00:19:31.839
in my situation. So that's one tool I've leveraged going forward that's really helped.

00:19:32.479 --> 00:19:38.079
I think practice in general is just really important in terms of getting your information

00:19:38.079 --> 00:19:44.239
out. And then I think getting as much feedback as possible from your managers is really important as

00:19:44.239 --> 00:19:54.880
well. Excellent. Thank you. Hey, Marlene, I see that you had a great question. Are you able to

00:19:54.880 --> 00:20:04.719
hop in and ask? Oh, one second. Okay. Sorry. Definitely multitasking. Squirrel. Hi. No,

00:20:04.719 --> 00:20:14.000
thanks for joining us. And my question is more about the little and or big wins. Like what's

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:17.680
the thing that you've done recently that you're just proud of? And it doesn't really matter if

00:20:17.680 --> 00:20:23.439
it's like launching a big model. Maybe it's just that you stood up to a work bully. I don't care

00:20:23.439 --> 00:20:29.199
what it is, right? I just kind of wanted to get a sense of somebody else outside my profession that

00:20:29.199 --> 00:20:33.760
has an accomplishment that they're proud of. Yeah, totally. I'll actually give one from a

