career advice. And I'm wondering if there's a piece of meaningful career advice that either

00:41:25.199 --> 00:41:28.479
you've received or you've given others that you'd like to share with us.

00:41:28.560 --> 00:41:33.600
I think there's a... Fortunately, I have really good mentors and leaders throughout my career,

00:41:33.600 --> 00:41:38.080
so I've received some very good pieces of advice. But I think the one that really stood out to me

00:41:38.080 --> 00:41:47.040
was if you are the expert in the room, and I mean on average, it's probably time for you to move on

00:41:47.040 --> 00:41:52.159
from your current role. Because there isn't a lot of people there to really help you grow and learn.

00:41:52.159 --> 00:41:57.840
I've been the opposite of the expert on certain teams, and those are situations where I might have

00:41:57.840 --> 00:42:04.399
gone home and I had imposter syndrome every single day, but I did learn the most during that time

00:42:04.399 --> 00:42:07.120
period. And so I think it was an important experience for me to have.

00:42:10.080 --> 00:42:14.959
Thank you. I see, Ryan, you had a follow-up question when we were talking about the

00:42:14.959 --> 00:42:18.080
strategy and analytics course. Do you want to jump in on that?

00:42:18.080 --> 00:42:22.399
Sure, thanks. Yeah, just listening to that course, it sounds really interesting and useful.

00:42:23.040 --> 00:42:27.120
I just had mentioned that if you don't have a link to the course syllabus itself, which you

00:42:27.120 --> 00:42:33.760
probably don't, maybe you have some ideas of some resources that we could look into ourselves or

00:42:33.760 --> 00:42:39.120
something that could approximate that content. So I don't... I could try and find it. I don't

00:42:39.120 --> 00:42:46.320
think I have it anymore, but I can try and find it. I don't think I have it, but I can try and

00:42:47.280 --> 00:42:56.239
find it. But really all it was, it was data sets from a business, and he made a regression model,

00:42:56.239 --> 00:43:01.439
and he put it in a PDF and just gave it to us and said, hey, translate what this means for

00:43:01.439 --> 00:43:06.159
the business. You could do that. You could probably go on Kaggle, get data sets, build a

00:43:06.159 --> 00:43:10.479
model. It doesn't necessarily even have to be right for this situation. You can just assume it's

00:43:10.479 --> 00:43:16.560
correct. Personally, I would try to make the best model possible and then try and say, hey,

00:43:16.560 --> 00:43:22.159
what does this mean? And I think it's important to take a step back from the actual modeling

00:43:22.159 --> 00:43:29.919
process when you do that. I think that's actually a big... I don't want to say turning point might

00:43:29.919 --> 00:43:35.439
not be the right word, but I think a lot of analysts just get bogged down in that and forget

00:43:35.439 --> 00:43:39.280
about the business impact and the business implications of their work.

00:43:39.280 --> 00:43:45.520
And so I think focusing on that is really important. We've actually had our team focus on

00:43:45.520 --> 00:43:52.239
building a proprietary code, both code, but then also data visualizations that help translate

00:43:52.959 --> 00:43:57.199
our model results to the business leaders that I think has really helped. And that's something

00:43:57.199 --> 00:44:02.879
that's taken time. I've had a lot of the same team for two and a half years, and so I think that

00:44:02.879 --> 00:44:09.760
really helps in help telling the story. That actually goes back to... That actually reminds

00:44:09.760 --> 00:44:17.679
me of something else. I think it really helps to actually go back to your exploratory data analysis

00:44:17.679 --> 00:44:21.199
to help tell the story. I think a lot of people are trying to lean on the model results,

00:44:21.199 --> 00:44:27.040
but if you go back to some of your EDA, that can actually help provide a visual representation.

00:44:27.040 --> 00:44:30.399
And a lot of people are visual learners, so that can really help tell the story.

00:44:31.360 --> 00:44:35.439
Yeah, it's interesting. It sounds like you're kind of saying, don't worry so much about doing

00:44:35.439 --> 00:44:39.840
it right or wrong, just do it. And eventually it'll work its way into right.

00:44:41.520 --> 00:44:45.520
Well, I think modeling-wise, in an actual professional setting, you want to make sure

00:44:45.520 --> 00:44:50.320
you have the best model possible. I was saying just for this specific example, if you were going

00:44:50.320 --> 00:44:56.719
to go get Kaggle data and build a model and then try to extrapolate what that means for the business,

00:44:56.719 --> 00:45:00.639
I'm saying just do that, just because the focus is not on the model for this exercise.

00:45:00.639 --> 00:45:04.800
The focus is more on translating what those results might mean.

00:45:08.399 --> 00:45:13.199
Thank you for that question, Ryan. And I wanted to pitch just a little bit. I know that

00:45:14.239 --> 00:45:20.560
Acacia and Blythe from Articulation were on as guests last year, and their episode was

00:45:21.120 --> 00:45:24.879
fantastically fun, and they talked all about presenting and communication,

00:45:24.879 --> 00:45:28.800
and they just wrote a book. So I figured I would sort of put that in the chat for

00:45:28.800 --> 00:45:32.959
everybody if they wanted to pre-order that. It's called The Motivated Speaker.

00:45:34.560 --> 00:45:40.560
But I did see that we had another great question. Kim, are you available to ask?

00:45:43.840 --> 00:45:51.760
Yes, hi. Thank you. Sorry, first time here, so first question. Thank you. Yeah, my question was,

00:45:52.479 --> 00:46:00.320
you mentioned earlier on that you took some online courses yourself when you were looking to

00:46:01.040 --> 00:46:06.879
upskill. You did some data camp courses. And I guess I'm in a similar situation at the moment,

00:46:06.879 --> 00:46:11.600
and I'm wondering, I'm sort of weighing up formal qualification versus self-learning,

00:46:11.600 --> 00:46:16.239
and I'm wondering if you felt it necessary for yourself, not necessarily from an employer point

00:46:16.239 --> 00:46:21.679
of view, to have that piece, well not just piece of paper, but that qualification, or did you find

00:46:21.679 --> 00:46:27.199
the skills that you built yourself was enough in terms of, you know, skill set and being able to

00:46:27.199 --> 00:46:35.040
do the job in your domain? It's a tough question because you have the trade-off between the two

00:46:35.040 --> 00:46:40.000
years that I was in school versus had I not gone to school, would I have been able to make up the

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:46.639
difference in education? I think the degree gave me two things. It gave me a credential which

00:46:46.639 --> 00:46:52.399
opened doors, but it also gave me just personal confidence from getting validation and knowing

00:46:52.399 --> 00:46:58.000
that I talked to professors to get answers and to fill in some of those gaps. So I'd say for me,

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:05.760
yes, it was worth it, but I think for some people, I think you can figure things out on your own. It

00:47:05.760 --> 00:47:11.520
really just depends on your skill, probably your degree, previous degrees, previous education

00:47:12.879 --> 00:47:20.879
in that situation. Cool, thank you. Thank you. Sometimes during the Hangout when I see all

00:47:20.879 --> 00:47:25.840
these great questions, I'm kind of like creating this map in my head of how they all tie together,

00:47:25.840 --> 00:47:31.360
and so I see you were jumping, ping-ponging a little bit, but jumping back to communication,

00:47:32.320 --> 00:47:36.560
Kylie, I see you had a great question in the chat too. Want to jump in here?

00:47:36.560 --> 00:47:41.600
Yeah, sure, thanks. Yeah, I was just curious because you've talked a lot about communicating

00:47:41.600 --> 00:47:47.439
with stakeholders, and one of the things that I have found most difficult when communicating with

00:47:47.439 --> 00:47:54.000
non-technical people is how you communicate uncertainty because you can have a really nice

00:47:54.000 --> 00:48:01.679
plot, but there's usually some kind of uncertainty in whatever you're projecting or

00:48:01.679 --> 00:48:07.760
extrapolating, but they only see a line, even if you have confidence bounds, and so it's a really

00:48:07.760 --> 00:48:13.919
unintuitive concept for a lot of stakeholders, yet it's really important to communicate,

00:48:13.919 --> 00:48:20.000
and I just wondered if you had any tips or tricks or you've had particular success with a way of

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:25.919
visualizing uncertainty or talking about it? Yeah, I think it's a great question. So,

00:48:27.520 --> 00:48:36.159
I think it's one in my situation where it was actually not, yeah, somebody actually just said

00:48:36.159 --> 00:48:41.520
it, all models are wrong, but some are useful. That's a famous quote from George Box, and I

00:48:41.520 --> 00:48:47.040
think I actually try to reference that in a lot of my presentations that models are essentially

00:48:47.040 --> 00:48:52.479
just guessing using statistics, and a lot of the situations that we're in, there'd be no

00:48:52.479 --> 00:48:59.199
alternative way of measuring it. So, you have to first have buy-in from your leaders who are not

00:48:59.199 --> 00:49:07.280
in data science that modeling is the solution, and I think one mistake I guess I would say I

00:49:07.280 --> 00:49:12.959
made earlier on was when we presented model results, we presented basically the average

00:49:13.040 --> 00:49:19.280
results, like on average, the model says X, Y, Z. We've gotten more now into range of outcomes,

00:49:19.280 --> 00:49:23.360
and I think the range of outcomes has helped build more confidence in saying like, hey,

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:30.320
the model outputs a range between this value and this value, and on average, we think it's this,

00:49:30.320 --> 00:49:35.679
and I think that's helped get buy-in from a lot of leaders rather than point estimates.

00:49:37.199 --> 00:49:41.840
Great, thanks. I also think somebody else said something in the comments that I thought

00:49:41.840 --> 00:49:46.959
was very good too, is starting with the so what, and then it's almost kind of like reverse

00:49:46.959 --> 00:49:52.239
engineering it. You start with, hey, this is what our model says, and then you can get into some of

00:49:52.239 --> 00:49:58.639
the details from there. I do think you can lose higher level leaders if you start to get into the

00:49:58.639 --> 00:50:04.080
minutiae of your model, but I keep all that information in the appendix, and I oftentimes

00:50:04.080 --> 00:50:10.719
reference it as the presentation goes on. I had one instance where I was presenting to our CMO,

00:50:10.719 --> 00:50:17.199
and we got into a relatively complicated concept, but I had one box plot that was like there to save

00:50:17.199 --> 00:50:21.280
the day to help explain the difference between two groups that we were looking at, and so that

00:50:21.280 --> 00:50:30.719
really helped in that situation. I wanted to add a quick shout out to another event that's coming up

00:50:30.719 --> 00:50:35.919
and thought this might be helpful for people. I just learned what a model card is. I don't know

00:50:35.919 --> 00:50:43.679
if a lot of people know that term, but it's a way – it's a framework for organizing and presenting

00:50:43.679 --> 00:50:49.120
essential facts about deployed machine learning models, and Julia Szilagyi is going to lead a

00:50:49.120 --> 00:50:55.520
workshop demo on it this month, so that's January 29th that she's leading that, so I just put the

00:50:55.600 --> 00:51:05.919
link into the chat there as well. Let's see. Libby, do you see any chat questions we have missed?

00:51:07.760 --> 00:51:16.479
I see a few that it looks like we could circle back to, and one is from Saul. Saul,

00:51:16.479 --> 00:51:22.719
are you still available to ask? Yeah. Thanks, Noah, for all the information.

00:51:22.719 --> 00:51:27.679
I think one thing that I'm interested in is working with such large data sets,

00:51:27.679 --> 00:51:32.719
there's always these segmentation possibilities of you can slice things a thousand different ways.

00:51:32.719 --> 00:51:36.719
Do you have any recommendations based on your experience on how you go about finding

00:51:36.719 --> 00:51:41.600
meaningful trends and patterns? Because what I get into is I get a lot of analysis paralysis,

00:51:41.600 --> 00:51:45.760
and sometimes I don't even know where to start when there's millions and billions of rows.

00:51:47.120 --> 00:51:52.479
Yeah. I don't have a good answer, to be honest, and the only reason is when I was dealing with

00:51:52.479 --> 00:51:58.560
a lot of these large data sets, we had the technology to be able to use all of the data,

00:51:59.679 --> 00:52:06.320
and now at DraftKings, I focus more on aggregate data sets, so I haven't really had to run into

00:52:06.320 --> 00:52:11.199
that issue, but I know there's a variety of different techniques on dealing with large

00:52:11.199 --> 00:52:17.439
data sets that I definitely used in graduate school that you can use, like resampling techniques

00:52:18.239 --> 00:52:23.120
to take a look at. That's a good point. Thank you.

00:52:25.600 --> 00:52:31.120
Thank you. Noah, going back to our conversation about the different trimesters of

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:38.479
your career so far and on going back or becoming a manager, I thought it would be helpful to talk a

00:52:38.479 --> 00:52:46.399
little bit more about that. What was maybe most surprising to you about becoming a manager,

00:52:46.399 --> 00:52:51.120
or what did you learn through that process? I think the most surprising thing was just

00:52:51.120 --> 00:52:57.679
the volume of meetings and how your day-to-day changes. I went from basically in a world where

00:52:57.679 --> 00:53:02.000
I would have maybe one or two meetings a day, and I could just sit and build models,

00:53:02.639 --> 00:53:09.439
to a world where I had meetings from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., and I had a bunch of people messaging

00:53:09.520 --> 00:53:17.760
me all day needing stuff or asking questions. I think that change was just very different.

00:53:17.760 --> 00:53:24.399
My ability to spend time on modeling went down significantly. When I work on models now,

00:53:24.399 --> 00:53:28.959
it's typically before work or after work or just in my personal time because I'm interested.

00:53:30.159 --> 00:53:38.639
Then I think from there, that was a big surprise. I think that forced me into time management,

00:53:38.639 --> 00:53:45.199
forced me into really thinking about what it is that I want to be doing on a day-to-day basis,

00:53:45.199 --> 00:53:51.360
which has changed my responsibilities at work a little bit more to just focus on modeling now,

00:53:51.360 --> 00:53:56.560
as opposed to some of the more traditional analytics that requires more day-to-day work

00:53:56.560 --> 00:54:05.199
with our stakeholders. Thank you, Noah. I wanted to ask, while we're on the topic of management

00:54:05.199 --> 00:54:11.199
and being a manager, are there any things that you keep in mind when you're trying to create

00:54:11.199 --> 00:54:17.600
an environment for your team to grow or an environment to foster curiosity or foster

00:54:17.600 --> 00:54:22.879
innovation? Even if you haven't put them into practice yet, what are some things that you

00:54:22.879 --> 00:54:27.280
are thinking about? I know that you put a lot of thought into being a good manager.

00:54:27.280 --> 00:54:31.760
Yeah, absolutely. I think I was pretty nervous, to be honest, to be a manager for the first time.

00:54:32.399 --> 00:54:37.439
I read a bunch of management books. I think a lot of the data management books are really

00:54:37.439 --> 00:54:44.479
interesting, but a lot of those management best practices were created before analytics

00:54:44.479 --> 00:54:49.760
and data science were a thing, so you have to apply your own spin to it. I think first and

00:54:49.760 --> 00:54:54.159
foremost, you have to have management principles. You should really, really think about those

00:54:54.159 --> 00:55:00.800
principles and how you can apply those principles. My first job as a manager, I had very junior

00:55:00.800 --> 00:55:06.959
employees, and so my principles were very different in that role. My number one principle

00:55:06.959 --> 00:55:13.120
at that time was set my team up for success. If I ever had a situation where I was at a crossroads,

00:55:13.120 --> 00:55:18.000
I would think back to that principle. How do I set my team up for success? What action do I take

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:22.000
to set up my team for success? Some of the time, that would be like, okay, maybe I shouldn't get

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:27.760
involved as much and let this analyst who's trying to become a senior analyst take that work on his

00:55:27.760 --> 00:55:32.560
or her own to prove that they can do it on their own. Earlier on in that tenure, I might have said,

00:55:32.560 --> 00:55:38.239
hey, I have to step in because this is a junior employee. I think deciding on those principles

00:55:38.239 --> 00:55:41.520
is really important, and you're going to have different principles for different situations.

00:55:42.080 --> 00:55:47.120
The role that I have now, I have all senior employees under me, so the principles are

00:55:47.120 --> 00:55:50.479
not about setting up for success. These principles now are much different.

00:55:50.959 --> 00:55:58.719
Thank you. Oh, sorry, Libby. You go ahead. No, I was just kind of wondering what, as you're switching

00:55:58.719 --> 00:56:04.719
into having more senior people underneath you, what is the main thing you think about for them?

00:56:04.719 --> 00:56:11.120
Is it career growth? Is it instead of setting up for success, what is it? It's different

00:56:11.120 --> 00:56:18.159
in this situation because of business need, but it's also different because while they all might

00:56:18.320 --> 00:56:25.120
be at the same level, their technical expertise might be different, and what they want to do in

00:56:25.120 --> 00:56:30.000
the long term might be different. I have some employees who've been only at DraftKings their

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:35.199
entire life, or their entire career, I should say. For them, they're going to benefit most from my

00:56:35.199 --> 00:56:42.239
non-DraftKings experience and learnings from that. Then I have some who the work for them is just

00:56:42.639 --> 00:56:46.560
very easy, and so I just need to keep them interested by giving them more and more

00:56:46.560 --> 00:56:53.280
challenging projects. It really just varies person-by-person in this situation.

00:56:56.719 --> 00:57:03.679
I love that. Thank you. I know we have just two minutes here, and maybe one more piece of

00:57:03.679 --> 00:57:10.399
career advice type question. I know when we were chatting, you told me something that you

00:57:10.399 --> 00:57:15.520
do where you keep this detailed list of things that have happened over the last 10 years,

00:57:15.520 --> 00:57:21.679
and I keep thinking back that I wish I was doing that. I was wondering if you could just tell us

00:57:21.679 --> 00:57:27.679
a little bit more about that and how that's been helpful for you. A lot of it, honestly,

00:57:27.679 --> 00:57:37.360
is what not to do. I'm a little bit of a cynical person, admittedly, so what I've noticed is when

00:57:37.439 --> 00:57:42.239
what I've noticed is when somebody makes a mistake, it sticks out to me, so I try and keep

00:57:42.800 --> 00:57:47.760
a note of like, hey, this didn't go well. Other people in the company were upset about this. There

00:57:47.760 --> 00:57:53.600
was a lot of internal talking about this specific thing, so I'll take note about, hey, this is what

00:57:53.600 --> 00:57:59.520
not to do. A lot of that is also in terms of management. If I had issues with the previous

00:57:59.520 --> 00:58:03.280
manager or I didn't like how something was communicated or something like that, I'll take

00:58:03.280 --> 00:58:09.120
note of how that communication happened just so that I don't do that in the future. Then I think

00:58:09.120 --> 00:58:17.280
back to what I have enjoyed in my roles over time, and I think about this periodically. A lot of

00:58:17.280 --> 00:58:21.120
times, this will be when I go get back from a vacation and I'm fresh and I'm just thinking,

00:58:21.120 --> 00:58:26.959
hey, what makes me happy at work? I try to just take a note of that. I don't do that every single

00:58:26.959 --> 00:58:33.199
day, I would say, but if something really stands out, I'll add it to my list. That's one of my

00:58:33.280 --> 00:58:39.600
favorite things to do coming back from vacation, before you open your computer. What is in my

00:58:39.600 --> 00:58:45.280
mind right now and what do I see as important and what makes me happy? Now I'm thinking all

00:58:45.280 --> 00:58:53.919
of those should be in one place together so I can go see them all. Thank you so much, Noah, for

00:58:54.560 --> 00:58:59.840
taking the time to join us today. Thank you all for the great questions as well. It's so nice to

00:58:59.840 --> 00:59:03.760
see you all. Yeah, thank you guys so much. Really appreciate it. Take care.

